   <head>To the Reader.</head>
   <p>
      <seg rend="decorInit">S</seg>Oothing and Crossing are two humours more trou<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>blesome than profitable, The one troubles the wise that loue no flatterie, and the other fooles that loue to be flattered. What you are I know not, and there<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>fore as you finde your selfe, so fit your sense: And yet if you will not scorne a fooles counsell, be silent ra<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ther than crosse, for feare of quar<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>rels; and rather learne silence among
<pb facs="3"/> the wise, than sooth their sayings in their hearing, for their eares are iea<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>lous ouer their wits. But lest I make a great entry to a little house, leauing what you reade to your leisure, and the liking to your capacitie, I rest.</p>
   <closer>
      <signed>B. N.</signed>
   </closer>
</div>
